[normal]It has been estimated that there are (in 2011) approximately three quarters of a million of people born in Scotland who live in England, Wales or Northern Ireland, 
[normal]which
[normal] represents 15 per cent of the population living in Scotland; a smaller though similar
[normal] number of people born in England, Wales and Northern Ireland, live in Scotland. 
[normal] 
[normal]It is sometimes said that the era of BROADCASTING has ended and with it, the supremacy of the BBC. Neither of these notions is true. Very recent audience measurements by BA
[normal]RB show that some sort of television or download facility is switched on in a household for over 25 hours a week and the BBC’s two main channels gather over a quarter of “viewing” time.
[normal]   
[normal]See: 
[normal]http://www.barb.co.uk/viewing/weekly-total-viewing-summary
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]E
[normal]g
[normal]: 
[normal]A misogynist culture has recently been 
[normal]reported in British Universities and
[normal],,
[normal] while this is not a direct outcome of ‘the culture of the airwaves’ it 
[normal]should 
[normal]be 
[normal]established
[normal] that the broadcasting world, in its quest for “youth audiences” is NO
[normal]T abetting an
[normal]y such hostilities. See:
[normal]http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/university-for-women-your-chance-to-spend-thousands-to-be-bullied-and-intimidated-by-your-fellow-students-8973696.html
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] BBC news report said that there was a “statement 
[normal]TO[bold] the (house o
[normal]f Commons)” when it should have written that there was a statement 
[normal]AT[bold] the Commons – reporters should know what a preposition is, and use each one precisely; misuse can mea
[normal]n significant misrepresentation.  S
[normal]ee: 
[normal]http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-25
[normal]155188
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
